    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Studies on Anticancer Activity of Brassica Oleraceae Extract And Its Mechanism Of Action On Human Epithelial Carcinoma Cells HEp-2</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">RENUKA DEVI.J</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Anticancer Activity<br />Human Epithelial Carcinoma</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Mar-2013 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0109</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">fruits and vegetables in regular diet reduces the development of various cancers such as
breast, colon, lungs etc. Among the different plant groups Brassicaceae has gained research
attention due to their enriched content of glucosinolates. They are hydrophilic anionic
secondary metabolites whose hydrolysis products like isothiocyanates are found to have
chemopreventive activity against various degenerative diseases. In this study, red cabbage
(Brassica oleraceae var rubra) was extracted by maceration using methylene chloride and
fractionated the crude extract into different fractions by solid phase extraction. All the
fractions were enriched and fraction 3 was confirmed for the presence of sulforaphane by
HPLC. The amount of sulforaphane present in the purified extract was quantified using
external standard sulforaphane and found to be 75 Î¼g/ml. Comparative antiproliferative
activity of various fractions (fraction1, 2, 3) was studied using MTT assay in human
epithelial carcinoma HEp -2 and normal vero cells. Results showed that purified extract
concentration found to have closer IC50 which is equal to 58.96 microgram/ml (HEp-2
cells), 61.2 microgram/ml (Vero cells) and less than the crude extract 113 microgram/ml
(HEp-2 cells) and 125 microgram/ml (Vero cells). The purified extract of red cabbage
induced massive cell death in treated HEp-2 cells. Drug effect on cell proliferation was
evaluated by measuring the distribution of the cells in the different phases of the cell cycle
by flow cytometry. Cell plots revealed that purified extract could induce apoptosis in
addition to the cytotoxic effect and found to have 65.34 apoptotic cells lower than that of
15.1 apoptosis in untreated cells. Expression of apoptosis-related proteins was detected by
western blotting and RT PCR. Probable apoptotic mechanisms mediated through p53, bax
and bcl-2 were also examined. Further studies on signalling mechanism showed that
purified extract down-regulated the expression of bcl-2 (antiapototic), while up-regulating
p53, Bax (proapoptotic) proteins and caspase-3. This study indicates that purified extract
possesses significant antiproliferative effect in HEp-2 cells which could be mediated
through p53 induction, bax and bcl-2 signalling pathways. Red cabbage is a rich source of
phenolic compounds with the anthocyanins, carotenoids, vitamin C. Bioactive compounds
previously identified in Brassicaceae such as glucosinolates, ITCs were reported to possess
good antioxidant capacity. The antioxidant activity of purified extract was determined in
terms of 1, 1 diphenyl 2 picryl hydrazyl (DPPH) and the levels of Glutathione S
Transferase (GST) and reduced glutathione (GSH) as phase 2 inducers of xenobiotic
metabolism in Vero and HEp-2 cells. The results indicated that crude extract possess
higher radical scavenging activity in HEp-2 and Vero cells when compared to purified
extract. GST, GSH levels in extract treated Vero and HEp-2 cells were decreased when
compared to control cells. The antimicrobial activity of purified SFN was done by
diffusion method. Purified extract was found to possess good antimicrobial activity against
bacterial and fungal species. The study showed that purified extract may exert its
antioxidant stress by scavenging free radicals and controlling xenobiotic metabolism in
Vero and HEp-2 cells. Molecular docking was studied to determine the structure activity
relationship of sulforaphane with various apoptosis proteins such as p53, bax, bcl-2 and
caspases by docking using docking server. Molecular models were used to study the
interactions of SFN with various binding pockets in the apoptotic proteins. SFN was
successfully docked to all the proteins and their binding energies were comparable with 5
Fluorouracil (positive inducer of apoptosis). The results were appreciable and in agreement
with our earlier research. Thus purified extract of Red cabbage was found to possess
significant anticancer activity and also as a potent inducer of Phase 2 enzymes of
xenobiotic metabolism. Hence SFN from plant source can be developed as a promising
lead in adjuvant cancer chemotherapy.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/11476">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/11476</a></td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Appears in Collections:</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="/dspace/handle/123456789/6855">Ph.D - Thesis  </a><br/></td></tr>
</table></center><br/>
